  <!-- Slide 10: Key takeaways -->
  <Slide id="takeaways" variant="dark">
    <div class="content-slide takeaway-slide">
      <p class="overline">Wrapping Up</p>
      <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
      <ol class="takeaway-list">
        <li>
          <strong>Code is the action format.</strong>
          Agents act by writing code, running it, reading results, and looping.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The harness is where behavior lives.</strong>
          Context, tools, routing, permissions, continuation, and stopping rules shape the experience more than the chat UI.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Context is an engineering surface.</strong>
          RTK, search, compression, and command-output filtering decide what the model gets to think with.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Trust comes from gates, not vibes.</strong>
          Permissions, sandboxes, tests, rubrics, and eval loops are how agentic workflows become usable.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Own the smallest harness you can change.</strong>
          Start from OpenCode, OmO, Pi, or your own plugin, but keep the setup understandable, measurable, and editable.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <div class="closing">
        <p class="closing__text">Pick one real workflow. Make one loop measurable. <strong>Then own the harness around it.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Slide>

